                           The igns of fale Conception.
                           Fale Conception hath many igns, common with the true conception; as the uppreion of the flowers, depraved appetite, vomitings, welling of the belly, and of the breats; o that it is a hard thing to ditinguih the one from the other: only thee that follow are more properly the igns of a fale than true conception. For in a fale Conception, the face is ordinarily puffed up; the breats, that at the firt were wollen, afterwards become, every day more than other, ofter and lanker, and without Milk. In fine, the face, the breat, the arms, the thighs and groyns grow lank and meager: The belly waxes hard, as happens to thoe who are troubled with the Dropie, and almot of an equal roundnes; with many pricking pains, at the bottom of the belly, which have carce any intermiion; which is the caue that they can hardly leep, being encumbered with a heavy and dead burthen. It may be known alo by other igns, for in the conception the Male-Infant begins to move at the beginning of the third Month; for the mot part; and the Female at the beginning of the third or fourth Month: now where any motion happens, the woman ought to oberve whether he have any milk in her breats or no: if he have milk in her breats, it is a ign of true conception; if he have not, it is a ign of fale conception. Beides, in a true conception, the Mother hall perceive her Child to move on all ides oftner though to the right flank than to the left, ometimes up, ometimes down, without any aitance; but in a fale conception, although there be a kind of motion, which is not enlivened;


that proceeds from the expulive faculty of the Mother, and not from the Mole. The Mother hall alo perceive it to tumble always on that ide he lies, not having any power to utain it elf; beides, as he lies on her back, if any one do puh gently downward the burden of her belly, he hall perceive it to lie and ret in the place where it was puhed, without returning thither: beide, that which will confirm it more, is, when after the end of nine months the woman hall not come to her Travel, but that her belly till wells and is puffed up more and more, all the ret of the parts of the body growing thin and meager, this is a ign of a Mole, notwithtanding that many Women have been known to go ten or eleven months before their delivery.

IN the firt place he mut keep a temperate diet, having a great care not to over fill her elf after o great an evacuation; and indeed her diet mut be like that of wounded perons; neither are the tales of nures to be believed, who exhort them to fill after o great an emptines, telling them that the los of blood mut be retored, for thee are meer Fooleries;
for as for that blood which he hath lot, it is but unneceary blood, uch as is uually kept for the pace of nine months, which to void, is much conducing to her Health. Beides, their nourihment for the firt days, mut be but lender, for fear of falling into a Fever; beides, the abundance of milk, which it would bring into the breat, where it might be in danger of curding, or Apotematizing; and therefore for the firt five days, let her ue Broths, Panada's, potched Eggs, Gellies, abtaining from Fleh, or French Barley: In the morning, Broth will be expedient, at dinner, Broth, or Eggs, or Panada; and at upper, the ame with ome Gellies for the econd coure. If he intend to nure her Child he may feed more plentifully, and drink ome Barl • water, wherein ome Corianders, or Fennel •
<…> be put.

Or you may apply this Cataplam; take of the leaves of Night-hade, and Mellilot, half a handful of each, let them be boyled and extracted through a coure cloth, then add to them Bean-meal two ounces, Oxymel, and Oyl of weet Almonds, of each one ounce; of this make a Cataplam, and apply it. If the Dieae be be more prevalent, you mut ue more forcible Remedies, and among the ret this Fomentation. Take of the leaves of Mallows, Violets, Dill, of each one handful, flowers of Camomile and Mellilot, of each a mall handful and a half, boyl thee together, adding to them a little Wine and Oyl of Dill, or Mutard;


firt let the Breat be fomented with this, and afterwards with an Oyntment compoed of equal parts of new butter, Oyl of Violets and Hens fat. But if thee things avail not to diipate the humour, you mut oberve whether the inflammation tend either to a uppuration, or induration. If you find that it tends to a hardnes, you mut try all means to hinder it by the way of mollifying Plaiters; among which this is not a little experimented: Take the Marrow of a Calves leg two ounces, Sheeps-greae one ounce, Saffron four Scruples; Cumin-eed bruied, two Scruples; mingle all thee and make a Plaiter. If the inflammation doth not harden, but doth altogether tend to a uppuration, which may be known by thee igns; that is to ay, the increaing of the tumour, the beating and exceive heat and pain which rages about thoe parts o vehemently, that they do not admit them to be touched. But now the uppuration is to be hatned with hot and moit Medicines, which have an Emplatick faculty, for which purpoe this is much commended: Take the leaves of Mallows one handful, roots of Marh-mallows one ounce, boyl thee together, and when they are mahed draw them out, and add to them Bean-meal and Fenugreek, of each one ounce, the whites of two Eggs, Myrrh, and Aa faetida of each one dram, Saffron one cruple, mingle all thee together, and make a Cataplam for your ue; to this you may either add Capons-greae, Hogs-greae, or freh butter: If thee Remedies do not uddenly bring the inflammation to a uppuration, you mut then take of the hels of Snails bruied, and lay them upon the Cataplam in uch a manner, that the Snail-hells may come to touch that part of the tumour which is mot elevated and pointed; whence it appears that the matter will firt iue; if thee Remedies avail not, it will


be neceary to open the aid Apothume with a Lancet, and this mut be done when you are ure that the matter is ready to come forth, which may be known by thee igns, when the beating ceaes, when the Fever, the pain, and the Heat of the part do begin to diminih, when you perceive the place pointed, and raied, and enclining to a blackih colour. When the wound is open, you mut firt apply to it a digetive, compoed of an ounce of Turpentine, half an ounce of Oyl of Roes, and the Yolk of an Egg. After this, you mut cleane it with Honey of Roes, Turpentine and Barly-meal, or with the Oyntment of the Apotles, or the Oyntment called Aegyptiacum, then you may put on the top of the place, the Oyntment called Bailicon, or Paracelus plaiter which doth diget, cleane, carnifie, and cicatrize after a very extraordinary manner. This is furthermore to be oberved, that an Ulcer in the Breat is not eaily cured, if the Milk be not dryed out of the other Breat; and therefore the Milk is to be dryed up by keeping the Child from ucking, and by putting upon the Breats of the Woman, cloaths dipped in cold water, together with Bean, Barly, Vinegar, and uch other like remedies.

Thus Nature proceeds to perfect the Formation of the Heart, Liver, Brain, and other principle Members: All which things are ditinctly brought to pas from the Conception to the eighteenth day of the firt Month, at which time it is called Seed, but afterward it begins both to be called, and to be a Feature. But for the better retaining of thee things in memory, that Author did not amis who thought fit to comprehend them in thee following Veres.


Sex in lacte dies, ter unt in anguine trini;

Bis eni carnem, ter eni membra figurant.
                        
                        

Six days compleat to milk, thrice three to blood convert the eed;

Twice ix oft fleh do form, thrice ix do maive members breed.
